## 1. Tech stack (fixed — do not substitute)

- **Frontend:** Next.js (App Router) + TypeScript + Tailwind CSS + shadcn/ui + TanStack Query
- **Backend:** separate **Node.js + TypeScript API service** (Express with a clean modular structure; keep it framework-light). Do NOT put business logic in Next.js API routes/server actions.
- **Database:** PostgreSQL + **Prisma** (schema + migrations checked in)
- **Cache/queue:** Redis + **BullMQ** for ALL async work (emails, CSV parsing, fulfillment, reminders, PDF generation)
- **Auth:** **Auth.js** (self-hosted) — email/password + Google OAuth. The separate Express API verifies the Auth.js JWT in middleware.
- **Payments:** **Razorpay** (orders API + signature-verified webhooks). Money is ALWAYS integer paise + currency code. Never floats.
- **Validation:** Zod schemas in a shared package, used by BOTH web and API.
- **Deployment target:** three plain `node` processes — `web`, `api`, `worker`. 12-factor (env-var config, stateless API), container-ready, but do NOT add Docker/Kubernetes — I'll do that later.

## 2. Monorepo layout (pnpm workspaces + Turborepo)

```
/apps/web        → Next.js: sender portal + public recipient pages (/r/[token]) + internal ops console
/apps/api        → Express + TS, modular: auth, orgs, catalog, campaigns, orders, payments,
                   fulfillment, notifications, invoices, admin
/apps/worker     → BullMQ processors (imports shared services from packages)
/packages/db     → Prisma schema + client
/packages/shared → Zod schemas, types, enums, constants (single source of truth)
/packages/emails → React Email templates
```

## 3. Data model (Prisma; money = integer paise; every business table carries orgId)

- `Organization` — name, **gstin**, state code (needed for CGST/SGST vs IGST), settings JSON, branding defaults
- `User`, `Membership` — role enum **OWNER | ADMIN | MEMBER | FINANCE**, unique (orgId, userId)
- `Vendor` — name, contact, fulfillmentType **EMAIL | API | DIGITAL**, `serviceablePincodes`/regions, **cutoffDates JSON** (e.g., "order by Nov 1 for pre-Diwali delivery"), payout details JSON, status
- `Product` — vendorId, title, description, "what's inside" rich text, images[], category, attributes JSON, status; `Variant` — sku, title, **priceCents, costCents**, hsnCode, gstRateBps, isDigital bool, stockQty; `Collection` + `CollectionItem` (e.g., "Diwali 2026")
- `Campaign` — orgId, createdById, name, mode **SINGLE | CHOICE**, budgetCentsPerRecipient (CHOICE), messageTemplate (supports `{{firstName}}`), branding JSON (logo, accentColor), status **DRAFT | ACTIVE | COMPLETED | CANCELLED**, expiresAt, serviceFeeBps
- `CampaignProduct` — the single SKU or the choice pool
- `Recipient` — campaignId, name, email, phone?, **tokenHash UNIQUE**, status **INVITED | VIEWED | REDEEMED | OPTED_OUT | BOUNCED | REMOVED**, address JSON (recipient-entered; encrypted at rest), redeemedVariantId, redeemedAt, reminderCount, optOutAt
- `Order` — orgId, campaignId, **recipientId UNIQUE** (one order per recipient — DB constraint), variantId, priceCents, status **PENDING | CONFIRMED | SENT_TO_VENDOR | SHIPPED | DELIVERED | EXCEPTION | CANCELLED**, vendorOrderRef, **idempotencyKey UNIQUE**, exceptionNote
- `Shipment` — orderId, carrier, trackingNumber, trackingUrl, events JSON, deliveredAt
- `Wallet` — orgId UNIQUE, balanceCents, **heldCents**; `WalletLedger` — **append-only**: signed amountCents, type **TOPUP | HOLD | HOLD_RELEASE | CHARGE | REFUND | ADJUSTMENT**, referenceType/referenceId, **balanceAfterCents**, createdAt. Never UPDATE/DELETE ledger rows. All wallet mutations in a transaction with `SELECT ... FOR UPDATE` on the wallet row.
- `Payment` — orgId, provider RAZORPAY | BANK_TRANSFER, providerRef, amountCents, status, processedEventIds for idempotency
- `ProformaInvoice` + `Invoice` — number (sequential per org prefix), pdfUrl, GST breakdown JSON (per-line HSN, taxable value, CGST/SGST/IGST), totals
- `AuditLog` — orgId, actorId (user or SYSTEM), action, targetType/targetId, metadata JSON — written on every privileged action AND every order/campaign/recipient status transition
- `NotificationLog` — recipientType, channel EMAIL, template, status SENT | BOUNCED | FAILED, providerRef

## 4. Features as user stories (build in this order; each has acceptance criteria)

### Epic A — Identity & organization

**A1. Sign up & create org.** As a new user I sign up with Google or email/password, then create my organization with name + GSTIN + state.
✓ GSTIN format validated (15-char pattern) · state selection drives tax split later · lands on an empty dashboard with a "Send your first gift" CTA.

**A2. Invite team with roles.** As an Owner I invite colleagues by email with a role.
✓ FINANCE can view spend, top up wallet, download invoices — cannot create/edit campaigns · MEMBER can build campaigns — cannot access billing/org settings · ADMIN = member + team/settings · role checks enforced in API middleware (not just hidden UI) · invite emails with accept links · every invite/role-change audit-logged.

### Epic B — Catalog

**B1. Org-facing catalog.** As an HR manager I browse a curated catalog with search, category filter, and price-band filter (e.g., ≤ ₹1,500); I can open a product page with photos, description, what's-inside, and a delivery note showing pan-India coverage and the vendor's **order-by cutoff date**.
✓ Collections (e.g., "Diwali 2026") browsable · digital voucher products clearly badged · out-of-stock variants not selectable.

**B2. Internal catalog CMS.** As a PLATFORM_ADMIN (separate flag, not an org role) I CRUD vendors, products, variants, collections; set serviceable pincodes/regions and cutoff dates per vendor.
✓ Lives in the ops console area, inaccessible to org users · seed script creates 2 vendors (one EMAIL hamper vendor, one DIGITAL voucher vendor) + ~30 realistic SKUs + a "Diwali 2026" collection.

### Epic C — Campaign builder (wizard)

**C1. Mode switch.** Step 1: choose **"Everyone gets this"** (SINGLE — pick exactly one product) or **"They choose"** (CHOICE — set ₹/head budget, then pick a pool of products whose price ≤ budget; warn if pool has no voucher fallback option).

**C2. Message & branding.** Step 2: write a message with `{{firstName}}` personalization (live preview), upload org logo, pick an accent color. Branding persists as org default for the next campaign.

**C3. Recipient CSV import — address-less.** Step 3: upload CSV with name, email, phone(optional). **No address column exists.**
✓ Parsed in a WORKER, streamed, never in the request thread · row-level errors (malformed email, missing name) reported with row numbers, fixable inline · dedupe by email within campaign · UI polls a job-status endpoint with progress · manual single-recipient add also available · cap 10,000 rows.

**C4. Review & cost estimate.** Step 4: shows recipient count × max cost per head (SINGLE: variant price; CHOICE: budget) + service fee (campaign.serviceFeeBps, default from env) = **estimated maximum cost**, alongside current wallet balance. Activate is disabled if wallet balance < estimate, with a top-up CTA.

### Epic D — Wallet & payments

**D1. Razorpay top-up.** As Finance I top up via Razorpay checkout (UPI/card/netbanking).
✓ Server creates Razorpay order · webhook verifies signature, is idempotent (processed event IDs stored), appends a TOPUP ledger entry · UI reflects new balance.

**D2. Bank-transfer top-up.** As Finance, for large amounts I click "Pay by bank transfer": the platform generates a **proforma invoice PDF** with amount + bank details; a PLATFORM_ADMIN later marks the transfer received, which credits the wallet.
✓ Proforma numbered and stored · manual credit is audit-logged with actor.

**D3. Ledger integrity.** Balance and heldCents are derivable from the ledger; a nightly worker job recomputes and alerts on drift. Finance can export the ledger as CSV.

### Epic E — Activation (the money path)

**E1. Atomic activation.** Clicking Activate runs ONE transaction: validate (≥1 recipient, products priced/active, wallet sufficient) → append HOLD ledger entry for the estimated max, increment wallet.heldCents → campaign status ACTIVE.
✓ Insufficient funds = clean error, nothing partial · double-click safe (idempotent).

**E2. Batched invite fan-out.** On activation, enqueue invite emails in batches of 500 with staggered delays (protect sender reputation).
✓ Each email contains the recipient's unique link `https://<domain>/r/<token>` · token = 128-bit random, stored **hashed** (SHA-256), single-use, expires at campaign.expiresAt · invite send logged in NotificationLog.

### Epic F — Recipient experience (public, no login, mobile-first)

**F1. Redemption page.** As a recipient I open `/r/[token]` on my phone: I see the sender org's logo/color, the personalized message, and either the single gift or the choice grid. SSR, minimal JS bundle, fast on mid-range Android.
✓ First valid open flips status INVITED → VIEWED · invalid/expired/used tokens get a constant-time generic "link not available" page (no enumeration) · per-IP rate limiting on all /r/* routes.

**F2. Choose & address.** I pick a variant (size/option selector where the product has variants), enter name-confirmed shipping address with **6-digit pincode validation**, and see a serviceability check against the vendor's serviceable pincodes BEFORE confirming.
✓ On confirm, one transaction: recipient → REDEEMED with address + variant; Order created PENDING (idempotent on recipientId); HOLD_RELEASE for (budget − actual price) and CHARGE for actual price appended to ledger · a second submit attempt cannot create a second order.

**F3. Serviceability fallback.** If my pincode isn't serviceable, I'm NOT dead-ended: the page offers the digital voucher option at the same value instead.
✓ Voucher redemption follows the same order flow with the digital variant.

**F4. Opt-out.** I can click "No thanks" — status OPTED_OUT, full HOLD_RELEASE back to the wallet, a kind confirmation screen. One click, no guilt-tripping.

**F5. Tracking page.** After my gift ships I can revisit my link to see status and tracking number/URL.

### Epic G — Notifications (worker-driven)

**G1. Reminders.** Recipients still INVITED/VIEWED get automated reminder emails — spaced (e.g., day 4 and day 8 via BullMQ delayed jobs), **hard cap 3**, stop immediately on redemption/opt-out.

**G2. Bounce handling.** Email provider bounce webhooks flip recipient → BOUNCED, flagged in the sender dashboard. Sender can fix the email (re-invites) or REMOVE the recipient (full HOLD_RELEASE to wallet).

**G3. Transactional set.** Invite · reminder · redemption confirmation (to recipient) · shipped-with-tracking (to recipient) · weekly campaign digest (to campaign creator) · wallet top-up receipt (to Finance). All behind an `EmailProvider` interface: SES/Resend implementation + console/log implementation for dev. Never log PII or tokens.

### Epic H — Fulfillment

**H1. Provider abstraction.**
```ts
interface FulfillmentProvider {
  quote(items, address): Promise<Quote>;           // cost + ETA + serviceability
  createOrder(order): Promise<{ vendorRef: string }>;
  cancel(vendorRef): Promise<void>;
}
```
Implementations now: **EmailVendorProvider** (templated purchase-order email to the vendor with recipient address + packing note; order → SENT_TO_VENDOR) and **StubDigitalProvider** (marks digital orders DELIVERED immediately, records a placeholder code — real voucher API comes later). Every order flows through this interface.

**H2. Fulfillment worker.** Consumes `orders.fulfill` queue: PENDING → CONFIRMED → provider call. Retries with exponential backoff (max 5); terminal failure → status EXCEPTION with exceptionNote, surfaced to ops.

**H3. Order state machine.** Transitions allowed ONLY per the map: PENDING→CONFIRMED→SENT_TO_VENDOR→SHIPPED→DELIVERED, plus →EXCEPTION from any active state, EXCEPTION→CONFIRMED (retry/resolve), →CANCELLED only from PENDING/CONFIRMED/EXCEPTION. Illegal jumps rejected at the service layer. Every transition audit-logged with actor.

### Epic I — Ops console (internal, PLATFORM_ADMIN)

**I1. Order board.** All orders across orgs, filterable by status/campaign/vendor; **EXCEPTION queue front and center** (red badge count).
✓ Manual actions: advance status with tracking-number entry (CONFIRMED→SHIPPED→DELIVERED), retry fulfillment, substitute variant (with note), cancel with automatic REFUND ledger entry.

**I2. No silent failures.** Any order in EXCEPTION > 24h and any BullMQ job in the dead-letter state triggers an alert (email to ops + a visible banner in the console).

### Epic J — Sender dashboard & reporting

**J1. Live funnel.** Per campaign: **invited → viewed → redeemed → shipped → delivered** with counts and %, plus opted-out/bounced counts, actual spend vs held amount, and "returned to wallet" total.
✓ Numbers derived from statuses, cached briefly (30s) · CHOICE campaigns show a per-product breakdown of picks.

**J2. Exports.** Recipient-status CSV per campaign; ledger CSV for Finance.

**J3. Campaign completion.** When all orders are terminal (DELIVERED/CANCELLED) or campaign expires: remaining holds released, status → COMPLETED, completion email to creator, invoice generation triggered.

### Epic K — GST invoicing

**K1. Tax invoice on completion.** Generated PDF: platform seller details, org buyer details + GSTIN, per-line items with **HSN code, taxable value, GST rate**, and **CGST+SGST when supplier and buyer state match, else IGST**, service fee as its own line (SAC code), grand totals, sequential invoice number.
✓ Stored, downloadable by FINANCE/OWNER/ADMIN, emailed to Finance · math behind an `InvoiceService` with unit tests on the tax-split logic.

## 5. Non-functional requirements

- **Tenant isolation is the highest-severity concern**: every API query filters by authenticated orgId; write automated tests proving org A cannot read/mutate org B's campaigns, recipients, orders, wallet, or invoices.
- All mutating endpoints accept and honor an `Idempotency-Key` header. Cursor pagination on lists. Error envelope `{code, message, details}`.
- Rate limiting (Redis sliding window): strict per-IP on public /r/* routes; per-org elsewhere.
- Shared Zod validation on every endpoint; sanitize recipient-provided strings before rendering anywhere.
- Addresses and phones encrypted at rest (app-level AES-GCM); a scheduled job redacts recipient addresses 60 days after delivery.
- Indexes: `orders(orgId, status, createdAt)`, `recipients(campaignId, status)`, unique on tokenHash, `walletLedger(walletId, createdAt)`.
- Structured logging (pino) with request IDs; never log PII, tokens, or Razorpay secrets.
- Tests: **Vitest unit tests near-100% on money code** (ledger math, hold/charge/release, tax split, state machine) · integration tests (Testcontainers: Postgres+Redis) for auth, org-scoping, activation, and redeem · one Playwright E2E: signup → build CHOICE campaign → activate → redeem via token → order created → funnel updates.
- DX: seed script, `.env.example`, README with `pnpm dev` bringing up web+api+worker against local Postgres/Redis.

